<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Environmental Audit Committee Inquiry – Marine Protected Areas</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> by the Marine Reserves Coalition</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This submission is supported by the following Marine Reserves Coalition members:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Blue Marine Foundation</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Greenpeace UK</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Marine Conservation Society</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Pew Charitable Trusts</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Zoological Society of London</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Marine Reserves Coalition </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recommends that:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In-line with scientific advice,</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the UK government should establish well-managed marine protected areas (MPAs), covering at least 30% of representative habitats in UK seas that exclude all damaging activities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To achieve this, the next two tranches of Marine Conservation Zones (MCZs) must be ambitious in number and size, with appropriate conservation objectives and management measures.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Adequately sized and well-selected Reference Areas must be included as part of the MCZ network in order to achieve ecological coherence.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In-line with an ecosystem based approach to the management of our marine environment, MCZs should be managed at the site level, rather than on a feature by feature basis.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n the absence of perfect information</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, a precautionary approach must be taken with regards to decisions affecting our</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> natural capital</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There needs to be appropriate stakeholder engagement in the development of MCZ management measures, to ensure appropriate enforceable regulation is enacted.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Marine Reserves Coalition (MRC) is a group of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">five</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> UK-based </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">organisations</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">working collaboratively to protect the marine environment through the creation of highly protected marine reserves.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e encourage the UK government to commit to establishing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ecologically representative network of marine reserves </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK Continental Shelf waters by 2016, and throughout all UK Overseas Territories waters by 2020. We welcome </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Environmental Audit Committee’s (henceforth the Committee) decision to conduct an inquiry into marine protected areas (MPAs). </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The biodiversity and productivity of the world’s ocean is diminishing at an alarming rate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">esearch suggest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that we are in danger of losing entire marine ecosystems, such as coral reefs, within the next generation unless </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">harmful pressures are reduced and mitigated against now.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It has been estimated that g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lobally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 90% of large fish species, such as sharks, tuna and swordfish, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have disappeared </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">since the 1950s</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and many marine habitats have been fundamentally altered by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> human activity, such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">destructive fishing practices</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and coastal development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Well-managed MPAs are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> key tool in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the suite of measures needed for the effective</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> conservation of marine biodiversity. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If left alone, over time m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">any marine habitats can recover and become productive again, as proven by the science undertaken in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MPAs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the Irish Sea (Isle of Man closed area)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Georges Bank (USA)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cabo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Pulmo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (Mexico)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> As well as being used as a tool to aid recovery where damage has already taken place, MPAs are an essential part of the package of precautionary measures that are needed to prevent healthy ecosystems from becoming degraded in the first place.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The term ‘MPA’ covers a broad range of protection levels in the marine environment and is often used to describe areas that have been set up for purposes other than biodiversity conservation, such as fisheries management. This has led to over-estimates of global MPA coverage and an inflated sense of how much of the ocean is protected</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, even though figures still fall well short of international targets.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Recent guidance published by the IUCN aims to tackle this issue and provides further definition for MPAs.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">No-take MPAs, or ‘marine reserves’, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are the most strictly protected type of MPA, in which all extractive and potentially damaging activities are prohibited. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An evaluation of data from over 200 studies carried out on 120 marine reserves across the globe, showed that on average, biodiversity increases by 21% and biomass by 446%, inside reserves boundaries.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Furthermore, the same study showed some organisms were up to 161% more abundant and 28% larger within marine reserves. This kind of increase in size and number has been documented in the UK, in lobsters (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Homarus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">gammarus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> L.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) within the Lundy Island no-take zone,</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and in king scallops (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Pecten</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">maximus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) within the Isle of Man closed area.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Defra is currently considering whether to establish ‘Reference Areas’ which would be the English equivalent of marine reserves.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The plans for implementing the 27 so far approved MCZs.</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While the conservation objectives for the 27 approved sites have been outlined by Defra, detailed information on the implementation, including specific management measures and timelines has yet to be announced. We understand that specific measures will be determined following further site-specific advice from the Statutory Nature Conservation Bodies (SNCBs).  We note however the lack of clear and readily available information at this stage regarding the implementation of the 27 approved MCZs. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As outlined by Defra in the MCZs Designations Explanatory Note, the general management approach for each approved MCZ will be dependent upon the conservation objective(s) of that site, in order to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recover or maintain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">favourable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> condition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of the features listed for protection. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Favourable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> condition is described by Defra as being “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the condition that would be expected in the absence of significant anthropogenic pressures which have an adverse effect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.”</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The MRC stresses that the conservation objectives must be the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">primary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> factor </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">accounted for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">when determining the implementation plans and that the management of each site must be guided by the conservation objective(s) for that site. Further, we suggest that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">simply ‘maintaining’ features in their current state is not ambitious enough and that the conservation objective of all MCZs should be set to ‘recover’. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is particularly important in the context of UK marine ecosystems, many of which are in a degraded condition.</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We believe this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> would be in line with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Clause 117 (6) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(b) of the Marine and Coastal Access Act, which states that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> any reference to conserving</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a thing includes reference to “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(b) enabling or facilitating its recovery or increase.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">”</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are concerned at the lack of management measures in place for the MCZs. It is only when these are fully enacted that the process is complete. The enactment process requires the full demonstration of the potential economic and social benefits of MCZs and two way communication between the regulators and stakeholders to ensure appropriate regulations are adopted.  MRC members have a wealth of expertise in facilitating the implementation of workable regulations in areas such as Lyme Bay.  MRC members would be happy to work with the marine regulators to this end. For further information on this point, please refer to the expanded notes submitted by the Blue Marine Foundation to this Inquiry.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How those MCZs will be monitored, managed and enforced, and the needs of different stakeholders — including fishing, leisure and extractive industries — will be balanced against environment protection.</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The MRC does not agree with the ‘feature by feature’ approach to the management of MCZs.  ‘Features’ in the marine environment do not exist in isolation, but as part of interconnected ecosystems; impacts on and changes to the condition of one ‘feature’ will affect others within that ecosystem. Managing sites on a ‘feature-by-feature’ basis is counterintuitive to an ecosystem-based approach and in practical terms is an overcomplicated and expensive way to manage the marine environment, adding unnecessary costs at a time when funds are already limited. Instead, management would be most effective at the site level, with broad-scale conservation objectives. We also believe this is what is required by the Marine Act’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Clause 117 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(2) which obliges g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">overnment to develop “conservation objectives for the MCZ.” It does not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">state that there should be conservation objectives for each individual feature.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> A narrowly defined features-led approach also requires an excessive level of scientific ‘evidence’ for each individual feature. It is clear from scientific studies that a reduction of impact on the marine environment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">in general</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is needed.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The feature-led approach has made the designation process costly and slow, and disappointed the participants of the Regional Projects whose recommended sites have not been adopted.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst we understand that MCZs (unlike fully protected marine reserves) are intended to be multi-use MPAs, damaging activities must be banned throughout all of them. Bottom-trawled fisheries and scallop-dredging can never be compatible with the conservation of marine biodiversity and should be banned in all MCZs. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Reference Areas (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">no-take </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">areas in which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">all extraction, deposition or human-derived disturbance is removed or prevented) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are a critical component of the MCZ network; without these ‘control’ areas, it cannot be determined whether the conservation objectives of the MCZs are being met. They are key to improving our scientific understanding of the effects of human activities on the marine environment, and will make an invaluable contribution to the body of knowledge on the effectiveness and design of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MPAs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The exclusion of Reference Areas from the first tranche </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">compromises </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the ability to deliver an ecologically coherent network</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">here is a strong base of sci</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">entific evidence that suggests </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">no-take </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MPAs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> should form the core of any ecologically coherent network of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MPAs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Scientific recommendations suggest that 20 - 30% of the marine environment should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">no-take,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to enable adequate recovery and protection, and up to 40% to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">substantially increase long-term yields of over-exploited species.</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">,</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We understand that Defra intends to undertake a review of Reference Areas and it is our hope that through this process, much larger, viable and scientifically appropriate Reference Areas will be identified and included in the next tranche of designations, as advised by the SNCBs.  However, we have yet to see any further details or a timeline for this review.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We feel it is important here to raise the issue of budget cuts. While we appreciate that cuts have been made across government, it is Defra that has twice received the maximum budget cut of 10% both in 2010 and 2013. The MRC is concerned that the levels of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">funding for the monitoring, management and enforcement of MCZs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are hence likely to be inadequate going forward. We call for the recognition of the important work of the Inshore Fisheries Conservation Authorities, the Marine Management </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Organisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and the SNCBs in the management of the marine environment; both in the management and licensing of fisheries, and in the conservation of nature. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The plans to improve the evidence base for considering potential further Zones, including the priorities and funding of the research bodies that will undertake the necessary research.</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While we fully support and welcome further survey work to improve the evidence base, delaying designation because of a ‘lack of evidence’ directly contra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dicts the intention to use the “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">best </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">information currently available,”</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which has been the premise of the MCZ process from the outset.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Collecting comprehensive evidence on the presence, extent and condition of all features in all recommended MCZs is unrealistic both financially and practically.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> At present it seems unclear as to where funding will come from to manage and enforce MCZs, let alone effectively monitor them.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n the absence of perfect information we should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">take a precautionary approach to decisions affecting our</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> natural capital</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Decisions should not be based on wh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at we cannot prove, but</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">what we know – that our natural capital in the marine environment is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">suffering from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unsustainable levels of pressure, and that the designation of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MPAs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> represents an effectiv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e tool to arrest this decline.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e note that under the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Marine Strategy Framework Directive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, the government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">is required</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">pay regard to the precautionary </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">principle”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (MSFD 2012</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Recital 27</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) when establishing a network of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">MPAs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The UK Marine Policy Statement also makes clear that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recautionary </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rinciple should be applied consiste</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ntly in accordance with the UK government and d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">evolved </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dministrations’ sustainable development policy (UK MPS</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Policy 2.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We agree with the SNCB advice that any delay in the progression of sites due to lack of data on extent and condition is likely to have negative consequences for marine biodiversity.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What the balance of factors should be — social and economic factors, as well as environmental factors — in considering further potential MCZs.</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The MRC believes that throughout the MCZ process, socio-economic considerations have taken precedence over environmental concerns. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While socio-economic costs were included in the Impact Assessment, no attempt was made to quantify the benefits of the proposed network. In our view, this has resulted in a skewed representation of the cost/benefit balance of the sites, and fundamentally disregards the original driver of the MCZ process, which was the clear evidence of the decline of the health and productivity of our seas. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As well as directly protecting the marine environment, MPAs are able to deliver socio-economic benefits, through improved delivery of ecosystem services, as demonstrated in a recent report to The Wildlife Trusts by the University of Plymouth.</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This fact has not been highlighted sufficiently by the government throughout the MCZ process and has often been completely </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ignored. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For example, e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cosystem capital</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the sum of all goods and services provided to human enterprises by natural systems globally,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has been calculated at US $41 trillion per year,</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of which over US $</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">20 trillion is attributable to marine ecosystem services.</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A study by scientists in 2004 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">estimated that the cost of a global network of MPAs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that meets the target of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">protecting 20-30% of representative ocean habitat would have an annual cost of US</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> $5-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">9 billion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span><a name="_ftnref26"></a><a href="#_ftn26">[26]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a fraction of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">US $</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">20 trillion per year attributed to global marine ecosystem services.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The level of ambition in the programme to establish protected areas (including MCZs), compared with the need for biodiversity protection.</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The MRC believes that the level of ambition in the UK’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to establish MPAs has deteriorated as the process has progressed. What started as an ambitious plan back in 2009 to establish an ecologically coherent network of MPAs by 2012, has seen increasing delays and a reduction in the number of expected MCZs from 127 to just 27 (one of which – Lundy, was already established as an MCZ) with no Reference Areas. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We also note the change of ambition regarding the government’s aim for the MCZ network. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the (then) Environmental Minister’s statement of 15 November 2011, Richard Benyon stated that; ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Protecting our marine en</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">vironment is essential and the g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">overnment remains fully committed to establishing MCZs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">to contribute to an ecologically coherent UK network</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><a name="_ftnref27"></a><a href="#_ftn27">[27]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We note the change in wording with regards to this commitment in the MCZ proposals consultation document, published in December 2012 that states; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Defra expects to designate future tranches of sites </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">to contribute to a UK contribution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> to an ecologically coherent network of marine protected areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’ (p.17).</span><a name="_ftnref28"></a><a href="#_ftn28">[28]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18.93pt; padding-left:2.37pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As indicated in our response to the government’s consultation on the MCZ proposals, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">we expect to see an ecologically coherent network created at the UK level. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is essential that the final UK network of MPAs ecologically coherent and implements all the principles on coherence detailed in the original SNCBs network guidance including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">representativity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, connectivity and adequacy. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">concern</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed that Defra is presenting a misleading and over-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inflated picture of protection to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">media, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">public and stakeholders alike</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Defra’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> MCZ announcement, on 21 November 2013, it states; “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These will join over 500 marine protected areas that already exist in the UK.”</span><a name="_ftnref29"></a><a href="#_ftn29">[29]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This figure is the result of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Defra recently adding intertidal Sites of Special Scientific Interest (SSSIs) to the number of MPAs it claims we have. Firstly these sites are all intertidal estuarine sites, rather than truly marine, and secondly they are being double-counted, as they are all also designated as European Special Areas of Conservation or Special Protection Areas.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would like to endorse the recent report of the Environmental Audit Committee on Sustainability in the UK Overseas Territories (UKOTs).</span><a name="_ftnref30"></a><a href="#_ftn30">[30]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The UK has failed to implement adequate safeguards to the marine biodiversity in the UKOTs.  From Gibraltar to the Falkland Islands, to the Turks and Caicos, the UKOTs support 90% of the UK’s biodiversity. With appropriate local engagement, the UKOTs are a real opportunity to safeguard the marine environment with actions of global significance. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Chagos</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Marine Reserve is step in the right direction, but this work needs to be continued throughout the other UKOTs. We agree with the Committee’s recommendation that the government must respond positively to the Pitcairn Islander’s request to establish Pitcairn’s waters as a fully protected MPA. Engagement with all UKOTs is needed in order to establish significant networks of well-managed marine reserves throughout all Territories, to meet the requirements of the Convention on Biological Diversity, and to safeguard marine ecosystems for the residents of the UKOTs.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">27 January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">IUCN (2003). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Recommendations of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Vth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> World Parks Congress, in Durban, Sou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">th Africa (8-17 September 2003).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">  </span><a href="http://www.uicnmed.org/web2007/CDMURCIA/pdf/durban/recommendations_en.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">www.uicnmed.org/web2007/CDMURCIA/pdf/durban/recommendations_en.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> BLUE Marine Foundation, Greenpeace UK, Marine Conservation Society, Pew Charitable Trusts, Zoological Society of London</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Rogers AD, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Laffoley</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> D.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> (2011). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">International Earth system expert workshop on ocean stresses and impacts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">. Summary report. Oxford: IPSO</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Myers R, Worm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> B. (2003). Rapid worldwide depletion of predatory fish communities. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Nature</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> 423:280–283</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Peres, C.A. (2010). Overexploitation. In: N.S. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Sodhi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> P.R. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Ehrlich, ed. 2010</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Conservation biology for all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">. Oxford</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">: Oxford University Press. Ch.2</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Bradshaw</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> C, Veale LO, Hill AS, Brand A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">R.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">(2001). The effect of scallop dredging on Irish Sea benthos: experiments using a closed area. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Hydrobiologia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> 465(1):129 – 138</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Fogharty</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> M